<font color="#FF0000">TANKER</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan 11  6:17:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The Vietnamese condemned French colonialism and drove them out. They considered the Americans to be motivated by colonialism also. In many ways this was an accurate perception. We wanted to dominate Vietnam. We didn't want to establish a democratic government. We wanted to establish a pro-American government. If the United States cared about democracy, then why have we supported dictatorships, brutal regimes, and monarchies all over the world? When the United States got involved in Somalia, we took sides in the urban warfare in Mogadishu against Mohammad Farrah Aidid, and on the side of his rival. The rival warlord, whose name I forget, was probably very surprised and very happy that a very large number of American ground troops materialized from nowhere, invaded his country, and proceeded to fight on his side against his enemy. He was probably very disappointed when the Americans were unable to defeat Aidid, and eventually left. Could you conclude from this that the rival warlord was morally superior to Aidid? Can you conclude from the fact that the rival warlord and his followers were intially gleeful at our involvement that the majority of the Somalis welocomed our presence? If you assume that, would that alone be reason for us to be there? Even if for some reason you decide that the rival warlord is a &quot;good guy&quot;, and Aidid is a &quot;bad guy&quot;, you would still regret our involvement since we were unable to defeat Aidid, and took high casualties. This was what happened in Vietnam. Actually Vietnam was worse in the premise, much less the result, since Somalia had a humanitarian dimension which was totally absent in Vietnam. In Vietnam, we invaded another country, and took part in a civil war. We killed two million Vietnamese. Our government killed 57,600 of its own citizens by sending them over there. If you have sympathy for the South Vietnamese, the way to help them is not to extend the war. I presume you had sympathy for the Bosnian Muslims. At the peak of the Bosnian War, did you advocate sending 500,000 American ground troops into the heart of the conflagration? Would it be worth it to kill large numbers of Americans simply to greatly increase the number of Serbs killed? If you say &quot;no&quot; does that imply that you have any lack of heartfelt sympathy and anguish for the Bosnian Muslims? The United States did not have altruistic motives in Vietnam. Even if you thought it did, you would still deeply regret our involovement since it was a dismal failure. 57,600 Americans were killed, and we achieved absolutely nothing. 
